name: Midsummer Common Fruit Trees
short_description: Apples and pears on the common.
description: Publicly accessible fruit trees located along the edges of the common, near the River Cam.

name: Paradise Nature Reserve Wild Garlic
description: A marshy woodland area along the Cam where wild garlic (ramsons) thrives in the spring.

name: Incredible Edible Romsey Town
description: Pavement-side planters featuring rosemary, mint, and seasonal vegetables for local residents.

name: Trumpington Community Orchard
description: A volunteer-run orchard with over 40 varieties of local heritage apples.

name: Wandlebury Country Park Nuts
description: The wooded perimeter of the hill fort contains several mature nut-bearing trees.

name: Cambridge University Botanic Garden Edibles
description: Public-facing borders near the entrance often feature edible plantings and herbs.

name: Stourbridge Common Elder
description: Dense hedgerows along the towpath provide heavy yields of elderflower and berries.

name: Gog Magog Sloes
description: The high chalk ground offers excellent conditions for sloe picking in the autumn.

name: Darwin College Walnuts
description: Mature walnut trees overhang the public paths near the Mill Pond and island area.

name: Coldham's Common Blackberries
description: A vast common with long stretches of blackberry bushes along the cycle paths.

name: Incredible Edible Eddington
description: Edible landscaping in the new development featuring communal herbs and fruit bushes.

name: Cherry Hinton Chalk Pits Rosehips
description: Nature reserve with wild rose and hawthorn berries in a unique chalk soil environment.

name: Fen Ditton River Greens
description: Wild fennel and wild celery can be found along the riverbanks heading toward the Fens.

name: Coton Orchard Access Path
description: Public footpaths passing through/near historic orchards often have available windfalls.

name: Brampton Wood Samphire (Inland Alternative)
description: Though a bit further out, the saline Fen soils host coastal-style plants like Sea Aster in damp spots.
